China Stocks: BYD, China Vanke, Xinjiang Goldwind, Yunnan Copper

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-06-30T07:39:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-30/yunnan-copper-vanke-xinjiang-goldwind-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 33.59 points, or 1.2 percent, to
2,762.08. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  gained 1.5 percent to 3,044.09.  BYD Co. (002594 CH), the Chinese automaker part-owned by
 Warren Buffett ’s Berkshire Hathaway Inc., jumped 41 percent to
25.45 yuan on its trading debut in Shenzhen.  China Vanke Co. (000002 CH), China’s biggest developer by
market value, added 2.1 percent to 8.45 yuan, the highest since
May 3. The company has started work on its first project in
western Xinjiang’s capital Urumqi, the  Securities Times 
reported.  Guangdong Mingzhu Group Co. (600382 CH) surged by the 10
percent daily limit to 10.12 yuan after saying it received an
investment gain of 78.8 million yuan, through an affiliate,
according to a statement to  Shanghai Stock Exchange  yesterday.  Sichuan Yahua Industrial Group Co. (002497 CH), an
explosives maker, surged by the 10 percent daily limit to 19.35
yuan after saying it got the government’s approval to produce
detonators. The  production line  will have an annual capacity of
500,000 detonators, according to a statement to the Shenzhen
Stock Exchange yesterday.  Xinjiang Goldwind Science & Technology Co. (002202 CH),
China’s second-biggest turbine maker, advanced 1.4 percent to
14.93 yuan. The company said its board approved a plan to sell
as much as 5 billion yuan ($774 million) of bonds to fund
working capital.  Yunnan Copper Industry Co. (000878)  (000878 CH) climbed 2.4 percent
to 21.91 yuan. China’s Yunnan provincial government approved
Aluminum Corp. of China’s 7 percent stake purchase in the
controlling shareholder of Yunnan Copper, the smelting company
said.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  